# TypeScript type conventions

Apply when writing or editing TypeScript (`.ts`, `.tsx`).

## No `any`

- **Never use `any`.** Use precise types, `unknown`, or generics instead.
- Prefer `unknown` when the shape is truly unknown; narrow with type guards before use.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function handle(data: any) {}
const value: any = fetchSomething();

// ✅ GOOD
function handle(data: unknown) {
  if (typeof data === 'object' && data !== null && 'id' in data) {
    // narrowed
  }
}
const value: IApiResponse = fetchSomething();
```

## Interface prefix: `I`

- **Prefix interface names with `I`:** `IUser`, `IOrderItem`, `IApiResponse`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
interface User {}
interface OrderItem {}

// ✅ GOOD
interface IUser {}
interface IOrderItem {}
```

## Type alias prefix: `T`

- **Prefix type alias names with `T`:** `TUserId`, `TStatus`, `TNullable<T>`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
type UserId = string;
type Status = 'pending' | 'done';

// ✅ GOOD
type TUserId = string;
type TStatus = 'pending' | 'done';
type TNullable<T> = T | null;
```

## Summary

| Kind     | Prefix | Example        |
|----------|--------|----------------|
| Interface| `I`    | `IUserProfile` |
| Type     | `T`    | `TUserId`, `TResult<T>` |
| Value    | —      | No prefix (e.g. `user`, `fetchUser`) |
